# function to get y_true
def get_y_true(set, label_or_class):
    # get true labels of test set all batches
    
    # get all batches
    batches = len(set)
    #print(batches)

    # get all batches
    all_batches = []
    for i in range(batches):
        all_batches.append(set[i])

    # get true labels of all batches
    true_labels = []
    for i in range(batches):
        true_labels.append(all_batches[i][1])

    # get true labels of all batches
    y_true = []
    for i in range(batches):
        y_true.append(np.argmax(true_labels[i], axis=1))

    # convert y_true to class names
    y_true_classes = []
    for i in range(batches):
        y_true_classes.append(np.array(list(set.class_indices))[y_true[i]])

    if label_or_class == 'label':
        # flatten into 1D array
        y_true = np.concatenate(y_true)
        return y_true
    elif label_or_class == 'class':
        # flatten into 1D array
        y_true_classes = np.concatenate(y_true_classes)
        return y_true_classes

2.2. Plot Accuracy and Loss¶

In [ ]:
def plot_accuracy_and_loss(history):
    # Get the training and validation accuracy from the history object
    training_accuracy = history.history['accuracy']
    validation_accuracy = history.history['val_accuracy']

    # Get the training and validation loss from the history object
    training_loss = history.history['loss']
    validation_loss = history.history['val_loss']

    # Plot accuracy. Make training type 'b' and validation type 'bo'
    plt.plot(training_accuracy, 'b', label='Training Accuracy')
    plt.plot(validation_accuracy, 'bo', label='Validation Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Accuracy')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

    # Plot loss. Make training type 'b' and validation type 'bo'
    plt.plot(training_loss, 'b', label='Training Loss')
    plt.plot(validation_loss, 'bo', label='Validation Loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Loss')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

2.3. Classification Report¶

In [ ]:
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report
def print_classification_report(data_set, model):
    # Get the true labels
    y_true = get_y_true(data_set,'label')

    # Get the predicted labels
    y_prob = model.predict(data_set)
    y_pred = np.argmax(y_prob, axis=1)

    # Generate the classification report with zero division parameter
    report = classification_report(y_true, y_pred, zero_division=1)

    # Display the classification report
    print(report)

2.4. Confusion Matrix¶

In [ ]:
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

def print_confusion_matrix(data_set, model):
    # Get the true labels
    y_true = get_y_true(data_set, 'label')

    # Get the predicted labels
    y_prob = model.predict(data_set)
    y_pred = np.argmax(y_prob, axis=1)

    # Compute the confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)

    # Display the confusion matrix
    print(cm)

In [ ]:
# convert the code above into a function
def plot_misclassified_images(data_set, model, num_images):
    # get true labels
    y_true = get_y_true(data_set, 'label')

    # get predicted labels
    y_prob = model.predict(data_set)
    y_pred = np.argmax(y_prob, axis=1)
    print(y_pred)

    # get indices of misclassified images
    misclassified_indices = np.where(y_true != y_pred)[0]
    print(misclassified_indices)
    # plot first 5 misclassified images
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, num_images, figsize=(20, 20))
    for i in range(num_images):
        ax[i].imshow(data_set[0][0][misclassified_indices[i]])
        ax[i].set_title(list(data_set.class_indices.keys())[np.argmax(data_set[0][1][[misclassified_indices[i]]])])
        ax[i].set_xlabel('True: ' + list(data_set.class_indices.keys())[y_true[misclassified_indices[i]]] + '\n' 
                         + 'Predicted: ' + list(data_set.class_indices.keys())[y_pred[misclassified_indices[i]]])
        
        ax[i].axis('off')

    
    plt.show()

3.1. Construct Model¶

In [ ]:
def build_model(hp):
    model = Sequential()
    
    model.add(Conv2D(hp.Int('conv1_units', min_value=64, max_value=192, step=32), 
                    (5, 5), 
                    #strides = (2, 2),
                    activation='relu',
                    kernel_regularizer=l2(hp.Choice('reg1', values = [0.1, 0.3, 0.5])),
                    padding='same',  # Add padding
                    input_shape=(256, 256, 3)))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())  # Add batch normalization
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    model.add(Dropout(hp.Float('dropout_1', 0.3, 0.5, step=0.1)))  # Add dropout layer
    
    #model.add(Conv2D(hp.Int('conv2_units', min_value=32, max_value=96, step=32), 
    #                 (3, 3), 
    #                activation='relu', 
    #                #kernel_initializer='he_uniform',
    #                 kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.l2(hp.Choice('reg3', values = [0.001, 0.01, 0.1])), # L2 regularization
    #                 padding='same'))  # Add padding
    #model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    #model.add(Dropout(hp.Float('dropout_2', 0.3, 0.5, step=0.1)))  # Add dropout layer

    model.add(Flatten())
    
    model.add(Dense(hp.Int('dense1_units', min_value = 5, max_value = 25, step = 10), 
                    activation='relu',
                    kernel_regularizer=l2(hp.Choice('reg4', values = [0.01, 0.1]))))

    model.add(Dense(4, # 5, if including teddy
                    activation='softmax'
                    ))
    
    # learning rate
    initial_learning_rate = hp.Choice('learning_rate', values=[0.0001, 0.0005, 0.00001])
    lr_schedule = tf.keras.optimizers.schedules.ExponentialDecay(
        initial_learning_rate,
        decay_steps=10000, # initial = 10,000. lower decays faster
        decay_rate=0.96,
        staircase=True
    )
    
    opt = SGD(learning_rate=lr_schedule)
    #opt = Adam(hp.Choice('learning_rate', values=[1e-3, 1e-4, 1e-5]))
    #opt = SGD(hp.Choice('learning_rate', values=[0.001, 0.0005])) # 0.0001 is too low. gets stuck. 
    
    model.compile(optimizer=opt, 
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy', # hot encoded. penalizes incorrect based on confidence
                  metrics=['accuracy'] # what metrics to dsiplay while evaluating model
                  )
    
    return model

# use Bayesian optimization
tuner = BayesianOptimization(
    build_model,
    objective='val_accuracy', # 'val_accuracy' or 'val_loss'
    max_trials=10,
    alpha = 0.001, # default 0.0001; higher = more exploration; lower = more exploitation
    beta = 2.6, # default 2.6; higher = more exploration; lower = more exploitation
    seed = 42 #,
    #directory='random_search',
    #project_name='my_project'
)

# early stop
early_stop_acc = tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor='val_accuracy', patience=5)
early_stop_loss = tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=5)

# initialize epochs
epochs = 20

# Search for the best parameter set
tuner.search(train_set, 
                     validation_data=valid_set, 
                     epochs=epochs,
                     callbacks=[early_stop_loss, early_stop_acc] # early stop
                     )

3.4. Best Epoch for Training¶

3.4.1. Track Performance by Epoch¶

In [ ]:
# train model with full  number of epochs, without stopping early

model_full = build_model(best_hps) #create model_full using hps from best model
history_full = model_full.fit(train_set, 
                              validation_data=valid_set, 
                              epochs=epochs,
                              #callbacks = [early_stop_loss, early_stop_acc],
                              verbose = 0 # 0 = silent, 1 = progress bar, 2 = one line per epoch
                              )

# find best epoch by accuracy and loss
best_epoch_acc = np.argmax(history_full.history['val_accuracy']) + 1
best_epoch_loss = np.argmin(history_full.history['val_loss']) + 1
print('Best epoch by acc: %d' % (best_epoch_acc,))
print('Best epoch by loss: %d' % (best_epoch_loss,))
